96
00:05:34,726 --> 00:05:38,729
<i>♪ This is the beginning of the end ♪</i>
__

97
00:05:38,763 --> 00:05:41,315
<i>♪ I can see it
in your eyes ♪</i>

98
00:05:41,349 --> 00:05:43,734
<i>♪ In everything you do ♪</i>

99
00:05:43,736 --> 00:05:47,904
<i>♪ You're afraid to tell me
that we're through ♪</i>

100
00:05:47,956 --> 00:05:52,743
<i>♪ But I can tell
by looking at you ♪</i>

101
00:05:52,745 --> 00:05:56,546
<i>♪ This is the beginning
of the end ♪</i>

102
00:05:56,581 --> 00:05:58,915
<i>♪ You just
give yourself away ♪</i>

103
00:05:58,967 --> 00:06:01,752
<i>♪ With everything you say ♪</i>

104
00:06:01,754 --> 00:06:06,173
<i>♪ And though you never
told me we must part ♪</i>

105
00:06:06,224 --> 00:06:10,927
<i>♪ Still, I can read
the writing in your heart... ♪</i>

106
00:06:10,979 --> 00:06:14,931
Mrs. Daniels, would you like
to come with me, please?

107
00:06:14,983 --> 00:06:19,770
<i>♪ There's some little
something that I miss ♪</i>

108
00:06:19,772 --> 00:06:23,774
<i>♪ What has become
of the warmth in your smile? ♪</i>

109
00:06:23,776 --> 00:06:25,942
<i>♪ And where is
that little mischief ♪</i>

110
00:06:25,994 --> 00:06:28,578
<i>♪ In your good-night kiss? ♪</i>

111
00:06:28,613 --> 00:06:32,366
<i>♪ This is the beginning
of the end ♪</i>

112
00:06:32,417 --> 00:06:34,951
<i>♪ I can see
the thrill is gone ♪</i>

113
00:06:35,003 --> 00:06:37,371
<i>♪ Why let it linger on? ♪</i>

114
00:06:37,422 --> 00:06:41,792
<i>♪ Why lie to me and say
it isn't so? ♪</i>

115
00:06:41,794 --> 00:06:46,380
<i>♪ For when I hold you
in my arms, I know ♪</i>

116
00:06:46,431 --> 00:06:48,403
<i>♪ That this ♪</i>

117
00:06:48,404 --> 00:06:50,404
_

118
00:06:50,508 --> 00:06:54,638
<i>♪ This is the beginning
of the end. ♪</i>

119
00:06:54,640 --> 00:06:56,606
Hogarth: <i>Those were the
secretary's words?</i>

120
00:06:56,641 --> 00:06:59,393
"Under official review?"
Sounds like a tenure committee.

121
00:06:59,444 --> 00:07:01,611
The War Department
is auditing the project.

122
00:07:01,646 --> 00:07:04,614
The president wrote us a
check for $56 million.

123
00:07:04,649 --> 00:07:07,734
- A small price for freedom.
- Last month, and the month before that.

124
00:07:07,785 --> 00:07:10,153
12 a year since 1942.

125
00:07:10,204 --> 00:07:12,622
They're entitled
to an itemized receipt.

126
00:07:12,657 --> 00:07:14,791
Wellerstein: <i>They're going to
shut us down, aren't they?</i>

127
00:07:14,826 --> 00:07:16,493
Nobody's shutting us down.

128
00:07:16,495 --> 00:07:19,162
They're pot-committed.
They can't fold.

129
00:07:19,213 --> 00:07:20,831
All they can do
is keep betting,

130
00:07:20,833 --> 00:07:22,833
buy the pot or die trying.

131
00:07:22,835 --> 00:07:26,136
You're the laddie whose father's
in prison for gambling.

132
00:07:26,170 --> 00:07:29,639
<i>( Men murmuring )</i>

133
00:07:29,674 --> 00:07:32,175
The tech area's
going to be reorganized

134
00:07:32,226 --> 00:07:34,644
to focus on lensed implosion.

135
00:07:34,679 --> 00:07:37,097
Dr. Oppenheimer has asked
me to run the new group.

136
00:07:37,148 --> 00:07:39,452
Joy.

137
00:07:39,503 --> 00:07:42,205
You're handing the project
over to Charlie McCarthy?

138
00:07:48,095 --> 00:07:50,255
It's Isaacs.
Charlie McCarthy's a--

139
00:07:50,264 --> 00:07:53,049
A wooden dummy
on a ventriloquist's knee

140
00:07:53,100 --> 00:07:54,684
with Robert's hand
up your ass.

141
00:07:55,519 --> 00:07:57,053
We have a working design.

142
00:07:57,104 --> 00:07:59,889
And in the space
between a working design

143
00:07:59,891 --> 00:08:03,059
and a weapon that works,
empires burn.

144
00:08:03,110 --> 00:08:06,062
So, Dr. Isaacs,
how soon can you deliver?

145
00:08:06,113 --> 00:08:08,531
A month? A year? 10?

146
00:08:10,117 --> 00:08:12,285
I don't, um...

147
00:08:13,904 --> 00:08:16,122
Well, I'd have to, uh...

148
00:08:20,945 --> 00:08:22,712
Dr. Oppenheimer.

149
00:08:22,747 --> 00:08:24,914
Do you ride, Charlie?

150
00:08:24,916 --> 00:08:28,752
I'm a Jew
from St. Louis.

151
00:08:28,803 --> 00:08:30,503
When a horse
won't take the saddle,

152
00:08:30,554 --> 00:08:32,922
you can send it
to the glue factory.

153
00:08:32,924 --> 00:08:34,557
It's not an option
with physicists.

154
00:08:34,592 --> 00:08:37,260
They're still in there
debating the science.

155
00:08:37,311 --> 00:08:38,928
Not a lot of fans
of implosion.

156
00:08:38,930 --> 00:08:40,764
<i>20 old men out of 2,000.</i>

157
00:08:40,766 --> 00:08:42,265
Win the confidence
of the Indians,

158
00:08:42,316 --> 00:08:43,933
chiefs will fall in line.

159
00:08:45,936 --> 00:08:48,271
You gonna make an
announcement to the staff?

160
00:08:48,322 --> 00:08:49,773
You are.

161
00:08:58,332 --> 00:09:01,117
Where's Frank Winter?

162
00:09:01,168 --> 00:09:02,952
It's just implosion
is Frank's baby.

163
00:09:02,954 --> 00:09:05,121
You're going to
have to deliver it.

164
00:09:05,172 --> 00:09:06,589
In 50 years, no one will know

165
00:09:06,624 --> 00:09:08,124
the name Frank Winter,
but yours--

166
00:09:08,175 --> 00:09:10,535
I can't take credit
for someone else's work.

167
00:09:13,597 --> 00:09:15,765
You made your career stealing
the work of another physicist

168
00:09:15,800 --> 00:09:17,434
and passing it off
as your own.

169
00:09:21,188 --> 00:09:23,807
Glen Babbive gave
an interesting exit interview.

170
00:09:35,820 --> 00:09:37,787
Then why'd you pick me
for the job?

171
00:09:39,206 --> 00:09:41,124
Saddle the horse, Charlie.

172
00:09:41,158 --> 00:09:44,598
I assure you, there's more
profit in moving forward.

173
00:09:46,464 --> 00:09:48,214
( Knocks )

174
00:09:51,385 --> 00:09:52,669
Dr. Winter?

175
00:09:52,671 --> 00:09:54,471
He hasn't been home
in two days.

176
00:09:54,505 --> 00:09:56,639
He's probably in his office
hiding behind an equation.

177
00:09:56,674 --> 00:09:57,841
Ma'am, we're not here
for your husband.

178
00:09:57,892 --> 00:09:59,843
We're here for your things.

179
00:09:59,894 --> 00:10:01,845
- My--
- Personal effects.

180
00:10:01,896 --> 00:10:03,513
Furniture stays
with the house.

181
00:10:03,515 --> 00:10:06,182
We have you slotted for a
duplex apartment in Row H.

182
00:10:06,233 --> 00:10:08,685
In regard to your husband.

183
00:10:12,239 --> 00:10:15,191
What does this mean,
"reassigned"?

184
00:10:15,242 --> 00:10:17,610
Who reassigned him?

185
00:10:17,661 --> 00:10:19,696
He put in for a voluntary
transfer three days ago.

186
00:10:19,698 --> 00:10:22,198
- Where?
- Even if I--

187
00:10:22,249 --> 00:10:23,700
You're telling me my husband

188
00:10:23,751 --> 00:10:26,202
has abandoned his family
with no explanation,

189
00:10:26,253 --> 00:10:27,370
not even
a forwarding address?

190
00:10:27,372 --> 00:10:28,621
I'm sorry.

191
00:10:28,672 --> 00:10:29,873
We'll be back with boxes.

192
00:10:46,690 --> 00:10:48,858
That son of a bitch
always was crazy

193
00:10:48,893 --> 00:10:51,978
with his
indeterminate variables.

194
00:10:52,029 --> 00:10:56,699
C-A-L-L-I-E.

195
00:10:58,786 --> 00:11:01,070
I wonder how long before
Frank's daughter turns 18.

196
00:11:01,072 --> 00:11:03,740
I thought you packed off,
Crosley, for Omaha.

197
00:11:03,791 --> 00:11:05,492
Or was it Idaho?

198
00:11:05,543 --> 00:11:07,877
Dayton, Ohio, actually.

199
00:11:07,912 --> 00:11:11,047
Next stop on my whistle tour
of American boomtowns.

200
00:11:11,081 --> 00:11:13,883
Doesn't make any sense.

201
00:11:13,918 --> 00:11:16,669
Oppenheimer hands Frank the
project on a silver platter

202
00:11:16,720 --> 00:11:19,422
and he skips town for some
kind of secret promotion?

203
00:11:19,424 --> 00:11:21,424
Really?

204
00:11:21,475 --> 00:11:23,693
That's what you lured me
here to talk about, Fritz?

205
00:11:23,727 --> 00:11:25,428
- Frank's career path?
- Lure you?

206
00:11:25,430 --> 00:11:27,263
<i>What are you talking about?
I didn't lure you.</i>

207
00:11:27,314 --> 00:11:29,482
- Yes, you did.
- No, I got a note from--

208
00:11:31,318 --> 00:11:32,902
Oh, it's the duchess

209
00:11:32,937 --> 00:11:35,271
and the boy with
his finger in the dike.

210
00:11:35,322 --> 00:11:37,722
Just give him five minutes.

211
00:11:39,109 --> 00:11:40,527
Charlie: <i>There's going
to be an announcement.</i>

212
00:11:40,578 --> 00:11:41,978
I'm taking over
the implosion group.

213
00:11:41,996 --> 00:11:43,413
Fritz: You?

214
00:11:43,447 --> 00:11:45,698
None of the Indian maids
available, eh?

215
00:11:45,749 --> 00:11:47,917
I need to reach Frank.
Have your heard anything?

216
00:11:47,952 --> 00:11:49,586
No more than Fritzy here,
I gather.

217
00:11:49,620 --> 00:11:51,120
They haven't told you
about their little

218
00:11:51,172 --> 00:11:52,755
scientific ménage à
trois, have they?

219
00:11:52,790 --> 00:11:54,290
Paul.

220
00:11:54,341 --> 00:11:56,926
So why would you
want to find Frank?

221
00:11:56,961 --> 00:11:59,546
You're the force of nature that
fills up the Frank-shaped vacuum.

222
00:11:59,597 --> 00:12:00,930
He's just trying to help.

223
00:12:00,965 --> 00:12:02,298
I see.
It's for her benefit.

224
00:12:02,349 --> 00:12:04,851
A bit of Kabuki theater
to impress a girl.

225
00:12:06,520 --> 00:12:08,438
Well, if I see Frank in Ohio,

226
00:12:08,472 --> 00:12:11,140
I'll be sure to send
along your regards.

227
00:12:14,311 --> 00:12:17,313
( Glass shatters )

228
00:12:17,364 --> 00:12:19,983
What did he mean?
What's a ménage à trois?

229
00:12:21,368 --> 00:12:22,648
I'm not trying
to impress anyone.

230
00:12:22,653 --> 00:12:24,954
I was in a bind.
Now I'm not.

231
00:12:24,989 --> 00:12:26,956
I think Frank helped me out

232
00:12:26,991 --> 00:12:29,742
and he's paying the price.

233
00:12:29,793 --> 00:12:32,328
And Oppenheimer
won't tell you where he is?

234
00:12:32,379 --> 00:12:34,797
We're not even sure he knows.

235
00:12:34,832 --> 00:12:36,132
Well, somebody does.

236
00:13:10,417 --> 00:13:14,370
Hey, X-4.
What's his name?

237
00:13:14,421 --> 00:13:16,372
That information
is not in our files.

238
00:13:16,423 --> 00:13:18,503
Well, I got to talk to him.

239
00:13:26,600 --> 00:13:28,051
<i>( Knocks on door )</i>

240
00:13:34,108 --> 00:13:36,609
- Hello.
- Abby.

241
00:13:38,062 --> 00:13:40,063
Um, he's not here.

242
00:13:42,232 --> 00:13:44,033
What? You want to
check under the bed?

243
00:13:44,068 --> 00:13:45,568
I'm not here to see Charlie.

244
00:13:55,462 --> 00:13:57,830
Is it true that you were
going to have a baby

245
00:13:57,881 --> 00:13:58,915
and then you didn't?

246
00:14:01,251 --> 00:14:03,086
Charlie told you that?

247
00:14:04,088 --> 00:14:06,839
Did you take care of it?

248
00:14:06,890 --> 00:14:08,257
What is this?

249
00:14:10,644 --> 00:14:14,597
Trust me, Helen, if I had any
friends here to turn to,

250
00:14:14,648 --> 00:14:16,265
any friends here at all...

251
00:14:18,902 --> 00:14:20,436
I need to know how
you went about doing it.

252
00:14:20,487 --> 00:14:22,271
Why would you want to do
a thing like that,

253
00:14:22,273 --> 00:14:24,473
Mrs. Ladies' Home Journal?

254
00:14:25,909 --> 00:14:27,110
It's private.

255
00:14:27,161 --> 00:14:29,662
I need to get dressed.

256
00:14:36,670 --> 00:14:38,671
Charlie wasn't
the only one who cheated.

257
00:14:40,524 --> 00:14:41,874
And he found out.

258
00:14:41,925 --> 00:14:44,293
You had an affair?

259
00:14:44,295 --> 00:14:47,096
Who's the guy?

260
00:14:47,131 --> 00:14:49,298
You don't know him.

261
00:14:49,300 --> 00:14:51,934
- But he got you pregnant.
- It's Charlie's.

262
00:14:56,523 --> 00:14:57,857
You sure?

263
00:14:59,693 --> 00:15:01,144
Yes, I'm sure.

264
00:15:06,950 --> 00:15:10,319
I had an abortion
two years ago in New Jersey.

265
00:15:10,321 --> 00:15:12,989
Doctor's probably practicing
medicine in a jail cell.

266
00:15:12,991 --> 00:15:14,907
But if you needed one now,

267
00:15:14,958 --> 00:15:16,659
you must have some idea
of where you'd go.

268
00:15:16,710 --> 00:15:18,161
You know it's a felony.

269
00:15:22,966 --> 00:15:24,133
Some of the girls in the dorm

270
00:15:24,168 --> 00:15:26,502
have been to a clinic
in Santa Fe

271
00:15:26,553 --> 00:15:29,505
near the bus stop
on Junction.

272
00:15:29,556 --> 00:15:32,175
You're supposed to say
you have obstructed menses.

273
00:15:35,562 --> 00:15:37,346
Did it hurt?

274
00:15:41,985 --> 00:15:44,520
Listen, Abby,

275
00:15:44,571 --> 00:15:47,273
I don't regret it.

276
00:15:48,024 --> 00:15:49,425
But you will.

277
00:15:57,367 --> 00:15:58,751
Do you love Charlie?

278
00:16:02,589 --> 00:16:04,207
Then you won't tell him.

279
00:16:19,022 --> 00:16:20,022
Woman on phone:
<i>Operator.</i>

280
00:16:20,057 --> 00:16:22,024
Yeah, I need an outside line.

281
00:16:22,059 --> 00:16:23,893
<i>Where to?</i>

282
00:16:23,944 --> 00:16:26,195
The Soviet consul
in New York.

283
00:16:26,230 --> 00:16:28,981
<i>I-- I'm not authorized
to make that call.</i>

284
00:16:29,032 --> 00:16:30,733
I'm authorizing
you right now.

285
00:16:30,735 --> 00:16:33,102
<i>Sir, even trying
to telephone the Soviets,</i>

286
00:16:33,137 --> 00:16:35,777
<i>you'll get yourself hauled into the
office of the secretary of war.</i>

287
00:16:35,789 --> 00:16:37,406
Do you have any idea
who you're talking to?

288
00:16:37,408 --> 00:16:39,792
<i>I-- no.</i>

289
00:16:41,628 --> 00:16:43,996
You got a pencil?

290
00:16:44,047 --> 00:16:46,749
My badge number is X-4.

291
00:17:02,613 --> 00:17:04,313
(Indistinct distant chatter)

292
00:17:06,238 --> 00:17:09,073
Do you sleep closer to the door
when you're home with Abby?

293
00:17:10,709 --> 00:17:13,044
What?

294
00:17:13,078 --> 00:17:15,713
People always end up
on the same side of the bed.

295
00:17:15,747 --> 00:17:20,551
It's like a designated
parking spot.

296
00:17:21,386 --> 00:17:23,471
It's old habit.

297
00:17:28,477 --> 00:17:30,557
Your marriage
is an old habit, too.

298
00:17:32,114 --> 00:17:33,781
<i>People fall back into it.</i>

299
00:17:36,118 --> 00:17:38,336
When's the last time
you saw Abby?

300
00:17:40,789 --> 00:17:43,758
In 36 hours...

301
00:17:43,792 --> 00:17:47,295
I need to lay out my vision

302
00:17:47,346 --> 00:17:49,297
for the future of the project

303
00:17:49,348 --> 00:17:51,766
to 2,000 physicists.

304
00:17:51,800 --> 00:17:53,601
I got nothing.

305
00:17:56,972 --> 00:18:00,452
Delay the announcement till we
figure out what to do about Frank.

306
00:18:01,477 --> 00:18:04,946
Agent X-4 seems to be
on permanent vacation.

307
00:18:04,980 --> 00:18:07,482
Why don't you just
tell the truth?

308
00:18:07,533 --> 00:18:09,784
Stand up in front
of the entire tech area

309
00:18:09,818 --> 00:18:13,454
and tell them G-2 made one of
the group heads disappear?

310
00:18:15,491 --> 00:18:18,159
Probably stick me in whatever
hole they stuck Frank,

311
00:18:18,161 --> 00:18:21,579
then you'd have to
run implosion.

312
00:18:21,630 --> 00:18:23,798
Why is that funny?

313
00:18:23,832 --> 00:18:27,335
I probably know the physics
better than you do.

314
00:18:27,386 --> 00:18:30,171
You think you could hold your
own against Oppenheimer?

315
00:18:30,173 --> 00:18:33,591
Those bloodsuckers
in the senior leadership?

316
00:18:33,642 --> 00:18:36,594
You think you can?
Oppenheimer picked you

317
00:18:36,645 --> 00:18:39,013
because he knows
that he can control you.

318
00:18:39,015 --> 00:18:42,400
All right.
You know, never mind.

319
00:18:44,403 --> 00:18:46,404
I have a speech to write.

320
00:18:47,656 --> 00:18:50,825
<i>( Door closes )</i>

321
00:18:56,865 --> 00:18:59,200
<i>♪ Oh, loving mother ♪</i>

322
00:18:59,202 --> 00:19:01,202
<i>♪ When the world's on fire ♪</i>

323
00:19:01,204 --> 00:19:04,205
<i>♪ Don't you want
God's bosom ♪</i>

324
00:19:04,207 --> 00:19:07,208
<i>♪ To be your pillow ♪</i>

325
00:19:07,210 --> 00:19:09,210
<i>♪ Tide me over ♪</i>

326
00:19:09,212 --> 00:19:12,013
<i>♪ In the Rock of Ages ♪</i>

327
00:19:12,047 --> 00:19:17,218
<i>♪ Rock of Ages,
cleft for me ♪</i>

328
00:19:17,220 --> 00:19:18,636
<i>♪ I'm going to heaven... ♪</i>

329
00:19:18,687 --> 00:19:21,856
Hey. I'm sorry...

330
00:19:21,890 --> 00:19:24,025
about your mother.

331
00:19:24,059 --> 00:19:26,227
- Was it unexpected or...?
- Excuse me.

332
00:19:27,446 --> 00:19:30,031
<i>♪ Tide me over ♪</i>

333
00:19:30,065 --> 00:19:32,533
<i>♪ In the Rock of Ages ♪</i>

334
00:19:32,568 --> 00:19:35,236
<i>♪ Rock of Ages ♪</i>

335
00:19:35,238 --> 00:19:38,239
<i>♪ Cleft for me... ♪</i>

336
00:19:39,908 --> 00:19:42,243
Um, can I help you?

337
00:19:42,245 --> 00:19:44,245
Man:
<i>Are you Meeks?</i>

338
00:19:44,247 --> 00:19:46,047
Yeah, Meeks.

339
00:19:46,081 --> 00:19:48,249
This isn't the Waldorf.
We're not bellboys.

340
00:19:48,251 --> 00:19:49,584
What are you doing
with my books?

341
00:19:49,635 --> 00:19:51,168
It's moving day.

342
00:19:51,220 --> 00:19:53,754
<i>Now that you're back,
get moving.</i>

343
00:19:53,756 --> 00:19:55,423
<i>♪ Loving brother ♪</i>

344
00:19:55,425 --> 00:19:57,892
<i>♪ When the world's
on fire ♪</i>

345
00:19:57,926 --> 00:20:00,261
<i>♪ Don't you want
God's bosom ♪</i>

346
00:20:00,263 --> 00:20:02,730
<i>♪ To be your pillow ♪</i>

347
00:20:02,764 --> 00:20:05,266
<i>♪ Tide me over ♪</i>

348
00:20:05,317 --> 00:20:08,102
<i>♪ In the Rock of Ages. ♪</i>

349
00:20:18,180 --> 00:20:19,914
Man:
<i>Attention!</i>

350
00:20:44,523 --> 00:20:46,140
You're not the Oberfuhrer.

351
00:20:47,526 --> 00:20:50,945
Is there any sign
of Colonel Cox?

352
00:20:50,979 --> 00:20:52,947
Colonel Cox
has been redeployed

353
00:20:52,981 --> 00:20:55,316
to a post more suitable
to his talents.

354
00:20:55,318 --> 00:20:57,438
Does he have those?
Talents?

355
00:20:59,321 --> 00:21:01,122
So that would make you...

356
00:21:01,156 --> 00:21:03,124
Colonel Emmett Darrow.

357
00:21:03,158 --> 00:21:05,638
The king is dead.
Long live the king.

358
00:21:07,129 --> 00:21:09,413
Well, I've squandered
enough of your time.

359
00:21:09,464 --> 00:21:11,332
High priests
at the security desk

360
00:21:11,334 --> 00:21:14,335
tell me my transfer form
is missing a signature.

361
00:21:14,337 --> 00:21:16,754
Leave it with the girl.

362
00:21:16,805 --> 00:21:19,140
All I need
is a drop of ink, sir.

363
00:21:19,174 --> 00:21:20,975
Dayton site expected me
two days ago.

364
00:21:21,009 --> 00:21:24,312
I won't bore you with
the technical subtleties.

365
00:21:24,346 --> 00:21:29,016
Harvesting polonium-210
for the neutron initiators.

366
00:21:29,018 --> 00:21:31,152
Dayton is adequately staffed.

367
00:21:31,186 --> 00:21:33,186
This hill,
on the other hand...

368
00:21:34,573 --> 00:21:35,906
is not.

369
00:21:38,360 --> 00:21:40,778
Sir, I can't stay
on this hill.

370
00:21:40,829 --> 00:21:42,446
It's a personnel matter.

371
00:21:42,497 --> 00:21:44,532
- Personnel?
- Personal.

372
00:21:44,583 --> 00:21:46,334
I can't work
for Charlie Isaacs.

373
00:21:46,368 --> 00:21:48,836
<i>It seems we both fancied
the same woman.</i>

374
00:21:52,207 --> 00:21:54,287
Would you close
the door, please?

375
00:22:09,057 --> 00:22:10,358
Get down on your knees.

376
00:22:13,862 --> 00:22:16,063
You're pulling my leg.
( chuckles )

377
00:22:16,114 --> 00:22:18,566
No one can see you.

378
00:22:18,617 --> 00:22:20,401
Take a knee.

379
00:22:20,403 --> 00:22:22,870
<i>Or did you change your mind
about the transfer?</i>

380
00:22:34,383 --> 00:22:37,585
Now...

381
00:22:37,636 --> 00:22:39,720
ask Jesus for forgiveness.

382
00:22:42,090 --> 00:22:44,425
I'm sorry?

383
00:22:44,427 --> 00:22:45,893
Jesus.

384
00:22:50,649 --> 00:22:53,401
Forgive me, Jesus.

385
00:22:53,435 --> 00:22:56,904
And what is the nature
of your sin?

386
00:22:56,938 --> 00:22:58,239
I don't know.

387
00:22:58,273 --> 00:23:02,109
Yes, you do.
It's weakness.

388
00:23:05,113 --> 00:23:08,699
God buried an atom under
a million tons of rock

389
00:23:08,750 --> 00:23:10,618
so that America
could split it in two

390
00:23:10,669 --> 00:23:12,586
and redraw
the maps of the world.

391
00:23:12,621 --> 00:23:15,873
And you want
to run off to Dayton

392
00:23:15,924 --> 00:23:19,084
because some girl didn't
ask you to the prom?

393
00:23:40,532 --> 00:23:43,684
Half the Hill woke up with eviction
papers tacked to our doors

394
00:23:43,718 --> 00:23:46,287
by order of the office
of the colonel.

395
00:23:46,321 --> 00:23:48,489
You picked a hell
of a week to leave town.

396
00:23:48,491 --> 00:23:51,492
I mean, not that you
picked-- oh, Jesus.

397
00:23:51,494 --> 00:23:54,929
You should talk to Jeannie.
She's got two dead parents.

398
00:23:54,963 --> 00:23:58,666
Jim, I'm so sorry
about your mother.

399
00:23:58,717 --> 00:24:00,301
They won't give you
more time?

400
00:24:00,335 --> 00:24:03,304
Uh, she'd want me here
serving my country.

401
00:24:03,338 --> 00:24:05,139
I don't even know
who we're serving.

402
00:24:05,173 --> 00:24:07,675
- Frank's gone.
- What?

403
00:24:07,726 --> 00:24:09,677
- Where?
- I don't know.

404
00:24:09,728 --> 00:24:11,808
But I know it's not good.

405
00:24:24,860 --> 00:24:27,161
So you're going to give it to
her on a bench in the plaza?

406
00:24:27,195 --> 00:24:28,946
I saved up for a hotel room.

407
00:24:28,997 --> 00:24:31,165
She's a virgin, right?

408
00:24:31,199 --> 00:24:34,668
Don't forget to sprinkle rose
petals on the bedspread.

409
00:24:34,703 --> 00:24:37,171
On E-3 salary?

410
00:24:37,205 --> 00:24:39,340
He'll be lucky
if the room has a bed.

411
00:24:39,374 --> 00:24:41,542
Liza:
<i>Where's my daughter?</i>

412
00:24:41,544 --> 00:24:43,177
Mrs. Winter-- Doctor.

413
00:24:43,211 --> 00:24:45,713
I think she's on an overnight
with the Mason Scouts.

414
00:24:45,747 --> 00:24:49,300
Yes, she was. And then she went
AWOL, apparently to meet you.

415
00:24:49,351 --> 00:24:51,352
Callie and I
had social plans.

416
00:24:51,386 --> 00:24:53,554
She took an early bus and we
were going to meet for dinner.

417
00:24:53,556 --> 00:24:55,973
Where?

418
00:24:56,024 --> 00:24:57,308
A restaurant?

419
00:24:57,959 --> 00:25:00,227
I'll save you a bus ticket.

420
00:25:10,238 --> 00:25:12,573
Are you going somewhere?

421
00:25:12,607 --> 00:25:14,041
Get in the car.

422
00:25:15,744 --> 00:25:17,962
<i>( Door opens, closes )</i>

423
00:25:26,054 --> 00:25:28,055
<i>( door opens )</i>

424
00:25:38,266 --> 00:25:40,351
I see you got my message.

425
00:25:40,402 --> 00:25:43,020
Prince of implosion.

426
00:25:43,071 --> 00:25:45,606
I'd have thought you'd
have better things to do

427
00:25:45,608 --> 00:25:47,942
than play grab-ass
with a telephone.

428
00:25:47,993 --> 00:25:51,028
What's wrong?
OSS can't take a joke?

429
00:25:51,079 --> 00:25:52,613
Strategic Services
is a clubhouse

430
00:25:52,615 --> 00:25:54,782
for overbred schoolboys.

431
00:25:54,833 --> 00:25:57,785
I serve at the pleasure
of a humbler master.

432
00:25:57,836 --> 00:25:59,837
General Groves.

433
00:26:01,089 --> 00:26:02,673
Freedom.

434
00:26:03,842 --> 00:26:05,626
<i>Nice office.</i>

435
00:26:05,628 --> 00:26:08,629
- A lot of turnover.
- Yes, well,

436
00:26:08,631 --> 00:26:11,432
the third time's a charm.

437
00:26:11,466 --> 00:26:12,800
You don't see it yet,
Charlie,

438
00:26:12,851 --> 00:26:14,551
but I am your friend.

439
00:26:14,603 --> 00:26:18,272
Most of my friends
have names.

440
00:26:18,306 --> 00:26:21,475
I want you to tell me the truth.
Can you do that?

441
00:26:21,526 --> 00:26:25,279
What do you think,
I'm some Bela Lugosi spook?

442
00:26:25,313 --> 00:26:28,482
I am the reason you're sitting
behind that desk instead of--

443
00:26:28,533 --> 00:26:30,651
Where?

444
00:26:30,653 --> 00:26:32,119
Where is Frank Winter?

445
00:26:32,153 --> 00:26:34,455
<i>You pack him off
to wherever it was</i>

446
00:26:34,489 --> 00:26:37,825
<i>you were going to send me
to torture him?</i>

447
00:26:37,876 --> 00:26:41,462
Ah, that's what this is.

448
00:26:41,496 --> 00:26:43,797
A soldier's loyalty.

449
00:26:43,832 --> 00:26:47,084
Let me guess. Frank isn't
the man I think he is.

450
00:26:47,135 --> 00:26:48,836
He wasn't.

451
00:26:48,887 --> 00:26:52,006
What about me? Am I the
guy you thought I was?

452
00:26:53,892 --> 00:26:57,311
<i>See, I don't think
you're a spook.</i>

453
00:26:57,345 --> 00:27:00,514
I think you're a bureaucrat.

454
00:27:00,516 --> 00:27:05,352
I think you're the guy at the border
checkpoint asking for papers.

455
00:27:06,688 --> 00:27:08,656
Hmm.

456
00:27:15,530 --> 00:27:19,700
Do you know the Banat
province in eastern Europe

457
00:27:19,751 --> 00:27:22,870
doesn't exist anymore

458
00:27:22,872 --> 00:27:25,205
except on a few old maps?

459
00:27:26,708 --> 00:27:28,125
Before Christ turned up,

460
00:27:28,176 --> 00:27:31,512
it belonged to the Thracians

461
00:27:31,546 --> 00:27:34,348
<i>until the Romans
bled them dry.</i>

462
00:27:34,382 --> 00:27:36,517
Then the Goths,
the Huns, the Gepidae,

463
00:27:36,551 --> 00:27:40,354
the Avars, followed by the
Slavs, then the Magyars.

464
00:27:40,388 --> 00:27:43,857
Four calling birds, three
French hens, I get it.

465
00:27:43,892 --> 00:27:45,526
Then the Hungarians
set up shop

466
00:27:45,560 --> 00:27:48,896
until the Ottoman Turks
cut them down.

467
00:27:48,947 --> 00:27:52,533
That's when
my family arrived.

468
00:27:52,567 --> 00:27:54,234
Merchants.

469
00:27:54,285 --> 00:27:56,904
Salt, mostly.

470
00:27:56,955 --> 00:28:00,541
They fought with the Serbs
to beat back the Turks.

471
00:28:00,575 --> 00:28:02,543
Then the son
of a Bosnian farmer

472
00:28:02,577 --> 00:28:05,829
put a bullet in a Hapsburg
and the world caught fire.

473
00:28:05,880 --> 00:28:09,750
<i>And then it became
the Banat Republic</i>

474
00:28:09,752 --> 00:28:12,970
for all of two weeks.

475
00:28:15,223 --> 00:28:19,560
It was a haven for Jews

476
00:28:19,594 --> 00:28:23,180
until the Axis rolled in
and Hitler...

477
00:28:23,231 --> 00:28:24,765
( laughs )

478
00:28:31,773 --> 00:28:36,193
Hitler solved the Jewish
problem once and for all.

479
00:28:36,244 --> 00:28:38,779
Now the Russians
are knocking at the gate.

480
00:28:40,627 --> 00:28:42,374
When you've lived in a place

481
00:28:42,399 --> 00:28:44,519
where borders
have no meaning,

482
00:28:44,546 --> 00:28:47,965
borders come to mean
a great deal.

483
00:28:49,918 --> 00:28:51,752
20 years I've lived
in this country,

484
00:28:51,754 --> 00:28:55,723
yet still I keep a packed
suitcase by the front door.

485
00:28:59,144 --> 00:29:00,761
Good.

486
00:29:02,597 --> 00:29:05,566
Let's throw it in the car,
go for a drive,

487
00:29:05,600 --> 00:29:07,101
pick up Frank.

488
00:29:09,771 --> 00:29:11,739
He's gone, and he's
never coming back.

489
00:29:11,773 --> 00:29:13,941
What does that mean, gone?

490
00:29:18,780 --> 00:29:20,164
He's dead?

491
00:29:22,951 --> 00:29:24,668
I don't believe you.

492
00:29:27,289 --> 00:29:28,872
You knew the man.

493
00:29:28,923 --> 00:29:31,959
Do you think Frank Winter
would surrender quietly?

494
00:29:31,961 --> 00:29:34,378
Sands shift during wartime.

495
00:29:34,429 --> 00:29:38,132
No one--
no one has tenure.

496
00:29:38,183 --> 00:29:41,969
The ones who survive
are the ones who adapt.

497
00:29:44,806 --> 00:29:47,274
Next time, call me directly.

498
00:29:48,643 --> 00:29:52,646
My name is Avram Fisher.

499
00:29:58,653 --> 00:30:00,154
Where are my manners?

500
00:30:00,205 --> 00:30:03,907
- Congratulations.
- For surviving or adapting?

501
00:30:03,958 --> 00:30:05,492
For the baby.

502
00:30:05,494 --> 00:30:09,213
Mazel tov to you
and your wife.

503
00:30:14,052 --> 00:30:17,187
<i>( Door opens, closes )</i>

504
00:30:37,082 --> 00:30:40,083
You invited Callie to dinner

505
00:30:41,034 --> 00:30:42,402
at a filling station?

506
00:30:42,554 --> 00:30:44,755
Ralph and Betty's Cafe.
This is it.

507
00:30:47,308 --> 00:30:50,060
<i>( Music playing )</i>

508
00:30:50,094 --> 00:30:52,930
( overlapping chatter )

509
00:31:02,957 --> 00:31:04,508
Where's my daughter?

510
00:31:18,807 --> 00:31:20,641
Elena?

511
00:31:21,810 --> 00:31:23,527
<i>( Door opens )</i>

512
00:31:26,197 --> 00:31:27,448
I sent her home.

513
00:31:30,318 --> 00:31:31,952
Where were you?

514
00:31:34,656 --> 00:31:35,823
Out.

515
00:31:37,826 --> 00:31:39,660
-<i> Abby.</i>
- Hmm?

516
00:31:39,711 --> 00:31:41,662
Is there something
that you need to tell me?

517
00:31:41,664 --> 00:31:43,997
You know, Charlie, I think
we dug up all the skeletons

518
00:31:43,999 --> 00:31:45,759
the last time you stopped by.

519
00:31:45,800 --> 00:31:48,418
I'm sure the neighbors
can give you a transcript.

520
00:31:48,470 --> 00:31:50,003
Are you pregnant?

521
00:31:59,013 --> 00:32:00,814
She told you.

522
00:32:03,852 --> 00:32:06,687
I had to hear it
from the Angel of Death.

523
00:32:06,738 --> 00:32:08,655
- What?
- Abby.

524
00:32:08,690 --> 00:32:10,023
Charlie.

525
00:32:14,245 --> 00:32:16,485
You were going to
sign the divorce papers

526
00:32:16,498 --> 00:32:19,199
and sneak out
the back door with Joey?

527
00:32:19,250 --> 00:32:20,834
This is a sign.

528
00:32:20,869 --> 00:32:22,836
I don't believe
in signs, Charlie.

529
00:32:22,871 --> 00:32:24,454
<i>Fine, it's better
than a sign.</i>

530
00:32:24,506 --> 00:32:28,208
It's a chance.

531
00:32:28,259 --> 00:32:29,877
It's too late.

532
00:32:34,265 --> 00:32:36,466
There's a lunatic in Europe

533
00:32:36,518 --> 00:32:39,052
making orphans out of a
thousand Jewish kids a day.

534
00:32:39,054 --> 00:32:41,188
You want two more to grow
up without their father?

535
00:32:41,222 --> 00:32:43,473
You think I don't know
about Europe?

536
00:32:43,525 --> 00:32:45,526
Honestly?

537
00:32:53,735 --> 00:32:58,205
You remember that first
doctor at Mass General?

538
00:32:58,239 --> 00:33:00,874
<i>The one who looked
like Calvin Coolidge?</i>

539
00:33:00,909 --> 00:33:04,912
A medical improbability.
That's what he called it.

540
00:33:07,549 --> 00:33:12,252
And I told you we could raise
Siamese cats for all I care.

541
00:33:13,755 --> 00:33:17,507
But you wanted
a daughter so badly.

542
00:33:17,559 --> 00:33:20,894
We both did.

543
00:33:20,929 --> 00:33:22,930
And you proved
the doctors wrong.

544
00:33:27,318 --> 00:33:31,939
Right out of the gates,
you said it felt like a boy,

545
00:33:31,941 --> 00:33:36,644
and you were right
about that, too.

546
00:33:42,917 --> 00:33:45,085
Thought I'd never
see you again.

547
00:33:45,136 --> 00:33:46,720
I mean, for all I knew,
you were dead.

548
00:33:46,755 --> 00:33:48,389
And then you came in the door

549
00:33:48,423 --> 00:33:52,559
and you said that
I poisoned our marriage.

550
00:33:52,594 --> 00:33:55,345
Listen.

551
00:33:55,397 --> 00:33:59,733
Whatever happened
between me and you

552
00:33:59,768 --> 00:34:03,353
or me and her

553
00:34:03,405 --> 00:34:05,939
- or you and--
- Charlie.

554
00:34:07,609 --> 00:34:10,611
It's not us.

555
00:34:10,613 --> 00:34:13,580
It's this place.

556
00:34:13,615 --> 00:34:15,949
I treated you
like every other jerk

557
00:34:15,951 --> 00:34:18,035
on this hill treats his wife.

558
00:34:18,186 --> 00:34:20,354
I underestimated you.

559
00:34:22,891 --> 00:34:25,225
I forgot what I had.

560
00:34:26,895 --> 00:34:29,062
But there's a kid in there.

561
00:34:29,064 --> 00:34:32,866
He doesn't know
his father screwed up.

562
00:34:32,901 --> 00:34:36,320
His world doesn't
even exist yet.

563
00:34:36,371 --> 00:34:38,739
We can do better.

564
00:34:44,913 --> 00:34:46,547
I can be better.

565
00:35:01,763 --> 00:35:03,564
It feels like a girl.

566
00:35:05,433 --> 00:35:08,235
<i>- ( Music playing )
- ( plates clattering )</i>

567
00:35:16,778 --> 00:35:18,612
Callie's on her way.

568
00:35:18,663 --> 00:35:20,530
Good.

569
00:35:20,582 --> 00:35:23,250
20 minutes, tops. There was
a message at the barracks.

570
00:35:23,284 --> 00:35:25,764
I goofed. I sent her to
the wrong restaurant.

571
00:35:27,956 --> 00:35:29,957
You left it in
your jacket pocket.

572
00:35:31,960 --> 00:35:34,795
So where were you really
going to meet Callie?

573
00:35:38,600 --> 00:35:42,936
Premarital sex
was not invented in 1944.

574
00:35:42,971 --> 00:35:46,291
There's a hotel off the plaza.
We haven't actually--

575
00:35:47,809 --> 00:35:49,776
I wanted to wait
until we were married,

576
00:35:49,811 --> 00:35:51,612
but I...

577
00:35:55,817 --> 00:35:58,151
Do you love her?

578
00:36:01,623 --> 00:36:03,824
She's the most perfect
person I've ever met.

579
00:36:07,378 --> 00:36:08,996
Is she happy?

580
00:36:17,639 --> 00:36:18,839
What?

581
00:36:20,842 --> 00:36:23,343
Callie took some pills
about a month back.

582
00:36:23,394 --> 00:36:25,634
Methyl something.
They were blue.

583
00:36:27,181 --> 00:36:30,817
Methylphenobarbital.

584
00:36:30,852 --> 00:36:32,602
They're mine.

585
00:36:32,654 --> 00:36:35,934
I don't think that she
was really trying to--

586
00:36:39,327 --> 00:36:43,196
She said it runs
in the family.

587
00:36:45,033 --> 00:36:48,201
There was an incident
when we lived in Ithaca.

588
00:36:50,204 --> 00:36:51,872
I made a mistake.

589
00:36:53,875 --> 00:36:57,210
Were you... trying?

590
00:36:59,681 --> 00:37:01,682
I know that Callie's afraid

591
00:37:01,716 --> 00:37:05,852
that she has what I have,

592
00:37:05,887 --> 00:37:09,389
but she's not like me.

593
00:37:09,391 --> 00:37:10,857
I spent half of my life

594
00:37:10,892 --> 00:37:14,227
looking for
a trapdoor out of it.

595
00:37:18,700 --> 00:37:22,069
<i>( Vehicles approaching )</i>

596
00:37:35,717 --> 00:37:37,918
Man: We picked her up
at a hotel in Santa Fe.

597
00:37:37,969 --> 00:37:39,252
Liza:
Callie!

598
00:37:39,303 --> 00:37:41,922
You can thank us
back at the Hill.

599
00:37:43,725 --> 00:37:46,059
Sorry, ma'am.

600
00:37:46,094 --> 00:37:48,054
If you took her away,
I'd never see her again.

601
00:37:49,931 --> 00:37:51,565
It's time to go.

602
00:38:13,616 --> 00:38:17,069
<i>( Door opens, closes )</i>

603
00:38:22,241 --> 00:38:23,659
How do you like your coffee?

604
00:38:23,710 --> 00:38:25,877
In my own living room.

605
00:38:25,912 --> 00:38:27,879
<i>2,000 miles from here.</i>

606
00:38:31,467 --> 00:38:35,220
<i>So what happens when a Nobel
laureate stays out past curfew?</i>

607
00:38:35,254 --> 00:38:37,422
You call out
the 101st Airborne?

608
00:38:37,424 --> 00:38:40,425
A Nobel laureate with a
packed suitcase in his car?

609
00:38:40,927 --> 00:38:43,061
Is that a crime?

610
00:38:43,196 --> 00:38:47,365
<i>Liza Winter, PhD, second
in her class at Barnard.</i>

611
00:38:47,367 --> 00:38:49,367
<i>Not a charm school.</i>

612
00:38:49,369 --> 00:38:51,536
I'm going to assume
you weren't born yesterday.

613
00:38:51,587 --> 00:38:53,672
I hope you'll extend me
the same courtesy.

614
00:38:53,706 --> 00:38:55,540
( Scoffs )

615
00:38:55,542 --> 00:39:00,178
Colonel Darrow, is it?

616
00:39:00,213 --> 00:39:02,798
My husband dragged us here
and now he's gone,

617
00:39:02,849 --> 00:39:04,800
and no one will tell me where
you're sending his check.

618
00:39:04,851 --> 00:39:06,802
So, under the circumstances,

619
00:39:06,853 --> 00:39:10,388
I would be grateful if I could
be released with time served.

620
00:39:13,226 --> 00:39:16,194
Colonel,
I can't spill secrets

621
00:39:16,229 --> 00:39:18,864
I wasn't entrusted with
in the first place.

622
00:39:22,235 --> 00:39:25,403
I understand you have a
job to do, but so do I.

623
00:39:25,405 --> 00:39:27,205
If you let me
just go back to Princeton,

624
00:39:27,240 --> 00:39:28,824
you'll never hear
from me again.

625
00:39:28,875 --> 00:39:30,915
Frank on tape:
<i>...set off a chain reaction</i>

626
00:39:30,960 --> 00:39:35,247
<i>that will explode with the
power of 20,000 tons of TNT.</i>

627
00:39:36,883 --> 00:39:39,634
<i>Powerful enough
to wipe cities off the map.</i>

628
00:39:41,387 --> 00:39:43,839
Liz on tape:
<i>Cities full of people?</i>

629
00:39:43,890 --> 00:39:47,759
You recorded
our conversations?

630
00:39:47,810 --> 00:39:49,530
Frank on tape:
<i>No, the Army will detonate it</i>

631
00:39:49,562 --> 00:39:51,346
<i>someplace where
it can't hurt anyone.</i>

632
00:39:51,397 --> 00:39:53,398
<i>When the Axis sees
what we're capable of,</i>

633
00:39:53,432 --> 00:39:55,267
<i>they'll have no choice.
They will have to surrender...</i>

634
00:39:55,269 --> 00:39:56,434
For how long?

635
00:39:56,486 --> 00:39:58,436
Your husband
is at another site

636
00:39:58,438 --> 00:40:01,606
proving his loyalty
to his country.

637
00:40:01,657 --> 00:40:04,242
You can help him by proving

638
00:40:04,277 --> 00:40:05,610
that you can be a discreet,

639
00:40:05,661 --> 00:40:07,863
productive member
of this community.

640
00:40:07,914 --> 00:40:10,081
Frank: <i>We're writing the
prologue to a new era,</i>

641
00:40:10,116 --> 00:40:12,117
<i>a history of peace.</i>

642
00:40:21,294 --> 00:40:24,763
<i>I've made mistakes.</i>

643
00:40:24,797 --> 00:40:26,631
<i>I've done things
I'm not proud of,</i>

644
00:40:26,682 --> 00:40:29,684
<i>but I swear I did all of it
with you and Callie in mind.</i>

645
00:40:31,304 --> 00:40:32,804
<i>A few months ago,</i>

646
00:40:32,806 --> 00:40:34,890
<i>a physicist from
another design group</i>

647
00:40:34,941 --> 00:40:36,641
<i>came to me and he told me</i>

648
00:40:36,692 --> 00:40:40,111
<i>that his model wasn't
going to work.</i>

649
00:40:40,146 --> 00:40:44,900
<i>So Reed Akley and I engaged
in a secret conspiracy</i>

650
00:40:44,951 --> 00:40:48,653
<i>to co-opt the resources
of his group for implosion.</i>

651
00:40:48,704 --> 00:40:51,289
<i>You remember Charlie Isaacs?</i>

652
00:40:51,324 --> 00:40:53,909
<i>We set him up
to cover our tracks.</i>

653
00:40:53,960 --> 00:40:56,127
<i>The irony is
the only way we were able</i>

654
00:40:56,162 --> 00:40:58,296
<i>to crack implosion
was by stealing...</i>

655
00:40:58,331 --> 00:41:00,966
I may know what it is
you're building here...

656
00:41:03,502 --> 00:41:06,504
but my daughter does not.

657
00:41:06,506 --> 00:41:09,391
<i>...but he had no idea.</i>

658
00:41:53,052 --> 00:41:56,388
( overlapping chatter )

659
00:41:56,439 --> 00:42:00,642
Man on P.A.: <i>Make sure your white
security badges are visible.</i>

660
00:42:00,693 --> 00:42:04,562
<i>All white badge holders
report to the PX immediately</i>

661
00:42:04,614 --> 00:42:06,898
<i>for the mandatory
staff meeting.</i>

662
00:42:08,401 --> 00:42:11,069
<i>The all hands tech area
staff meeting</i>

663
00:42:11,071 --> 00:42:13,238
<i>is beginning in the PX.</i>

664
00:42:13,240 --> 00:42:15,957
<i>Be prepared to present
your security badge.</i>

665
00:42:21,580 --> 00:42:24,799
( no audible dialogue )

666
00:42:34,260 --> 00:42:36,594
( muttering )

667
00:42:37,596 --> 00:42:39,431
Damn it.

668
00:42:39,482 --> 00:42:42,233
<i>( Footsteps )</i>

669
00:42:42,268 --> 00:42:43,818
They fix the PA?

670
00:42:46,272 --> 00:42:48,406
Where is he?

671
00:42:48,441 --> 00:42:51,242
The Army said Frank was
transferred to another site.

672
00:42:51,277 --> 00:42:52,777
One suit, one shirt,
one necktie,

673
00:42:52,828 --> 00:42:54,779
one pair of shoes?

674
00:42:54,830 --> 00:42:56,781
That's all he took.

675
00:42:56,832 --> 00:43:00,201
All his clothes
are boxed up at the house.

676
00:43:00,252 --> 00:43:01,619
He even left
his security badge.

677
00:43:01,621 --> 00:43:05,540
Does that sound
like a transfer to you?

678
00:43:05,591 --> 00:43:09,260
I don't know what law of
physics he's broken now,

679
00:43:09,295 --> 00:43:10,795
but I think you do.

680
00:43:10,846 --> 00:43:12,097
Man:<i> Ma'am?</i>

681
00:43:13,632 --> 00:43:16,112
Would you come
with us, please?

682
00:43:16,852 --> 00:43:18,636
It's all right.
Hey, she's fine.

683
00:43:18,638 --> 00:43:20,718
She doesn't have clearance.

684
00:43:21,474 --> 00:43:22,674
Where is he?

685
00:43:45,881 --> 00:43:49,084
All right, can I get
everyone's attention, please?

686
00:43:49,135 --> 00:43:50,802
Thanks very much.

687
00:43:50,836 --> 00:43:52,876
Can I have
everyone's attention?

688
00:43:54,340 --> 00:43:55,673
Thank you.

689
00:43:58,144 --> 00:44:00,311
Dr. Oppenheimer...

690
00:44:00,346 --> 00:44:04,849
asked me to say a few words
about the road ahead.

691
00:44:04,900 --> 00:44:08,060
But I want to talk about
the road that got us here.

692
00:44:09,355 --> 00:44:11,489
I had a teacher
in St. Louis.

693
00:44:11,524 --> 00:44:15,693
He used to say that science
isn't a quest for truth,

694
00:44:15,695 --> 00:44:20,115
but a process of
correcting your errors.

695
00:44:20,166 --> 00:44:23,366
We've racked up more than
our share on this hill.

696
00:44:25,004 --> 00:44:27,124
And I want to
correct one right now.

697
00:44:32,928 --> 00:44:35,513
The fact that
we're all standing here,

698
00:44:35,548 --> 00:44:37,549
that there is a path forward,

699
00:44:37,551 --> 00:44:39,134
we owe it to one man,

700
00:44:39,185 --> 00:44:40,802
and he isn't
standing here with us.

701
00:44:40,853 --> 00:44:45,640
The implosion model exists
because of Frank Winter.

702
00:44:45,691 --> 00:44:48,726
( Murmuring )

703
00:44:48,778 --> 00:44:52,530
He was the crank
in the wilderness

704
00:44:52,565 --> 00:44:56,151
rubbing two sticks together
when no one believed.

705
00:44:56,202 --> 00:44:59,370
He fed the spark.

706
00:44:59,405 --> 00:45:00,655
He fought off the wolves.

707
00:45:00,706 --> 00:45:04,576
<i>He corrected his errors.</i>

708
00:45:07,213 --> 00:45:09,453
You should be listening
to Frank right now.

709
00:45:16,222 --> 00:45:19,924
But the War Department
has asked him

710
00:45:19,975 --> 00:45:24,062
to take the reins on another
project at another site.

711
00:45:24,064 --> 00:45:26,014
Their gain is our loss.

712
00:45:26,065 --> 00:45:28,566
I talked to Frank on the
phone a little while ago.

713
00:45:28,601 --> 00:45:30,568
He gave me his blessing

714
00:45:30,603 --> 00:45:33,938
and I gave him
my sincere thanks.

715
00:45:33,989 --> 00:45:35,940
We all should.

716
00:45:35,942 --> 00:45:37,775
- ( Applause )
- Did he talk to him?

717
00:45:46,619 --> 00:45:48,453
As for the road ahead...

718
00:45:51,006 --> 00:45:52,624
there is no road.

719
00:45:52,626 --> 00:45:55,210
<i>We have to dig it
out of the dirt.</i>

720
00:45:55,261 --> 00:45:58,429
It's no longer a thought problem.
It's not a theory.

721
00:45:58,464 --> 00:46:01,432
We're all going home
with blood on our sleeves.

722
00:46:01,467 --> 00:46:02,967
We're going to build
a working gadget.

723
00:46:03,018 --> 00:46:04,302
We're going to
drop it on Berlin.

724
00:46:04,304 --> 00:46:06,437
If those doubting Thomases

725
00:46:06,472 --> 00:46:08,306
in Washington
don't believe us,

726
00:46:08,308 --> 00:46:09,807
then they can fly out here

727
00:46:09,809 --> 00:46:11,249
and stick their fingers
in the wound.

728
00:46:11,277 --> 00:46:15,063
'Cause on July 4th, 1945,

729
00:46:15,114 --> 00:46:18,983
we're going to put on the biggest
firework show since the Book of Genesis.

730
00:46:19,034 --> 00:46:22,237
We're going to test the
gadget in our own backyard.

731
00:46:22,288 --> 00:46:24,455
( Crowd murmuring )

732
00:46:24,490 --> 00:46:25,990
A nuclear test in a year?

733
00:46:26,041 --> 00:46:28,459
Whose bloody sleeve
did he pull that out of?

734
00:46:28,494 --> 00:46:31,574
He just pushed in all his chips.
It's a bluff.

735
00:46:32,831 --> 00:46:35,750
Charlie:
<i>Now, I've heard it said</i>

736
00:46:35,801 --> 00:46:39,504
<i>that physics is
a gentleman's sport.</i>

737
00:46:40,606 --> 00:46:43,575
<i>Some of you may think
I'm hitting above my weight.</i>

738
00:46:43,599 --> 00:46:45,226
_

739
00:46:45,227 --> 00:46:46,895
I'm 28 years old.

740
00:46:48,063 --> 00:46:50,181
<i>I grew up in Missouri</i>

741
00:46:50,232 --> 00:46:53,518
in a cold-water tenement.

742
00:46:53,520 --> 00:46:55,436
Red blood, not blue.

743
00:46:55,487 --> 00:46:58,072
<i>My mother used to scrub it
out of my school clothes.</i>

744
00:46:59,858 --> 00:47:04,862
See, I had to learn
to hit above my weight.

745
00:47:06,532 --> 00:47:10,034
<i>We all do.</i>

746
00:47:10,085 --> 00:47:11,965
<i>'Cause the guys
in the other corner,</i>

747
00:47:13,004 --> 00:47:14,872
they invented
quantum mechanics.

748
00:47:15,424 --> 00:47:19,043
<i>They split the atom.
They beat us to the punch.</i>

749
00:47:19,045 --> 00:47:20,795
That's another error
we're going to correct.

750
00:47:20,846 --> 00:47:23,681
<i>And when it's over,</i>

751
00:47:23,716 --> 00:47:25,883
<i>when we've corrected
that error in Germany</i>

752
00:47:25,935 --> 00:47:27,815
right off the face
of the earth...

753
00:47:29,722 --> 00:47:33,224
<i>then we're all going home</i>

754
00:47:33,275 --> 00:47:35,893
where we belong,

755
00:47:35,895 --> 00:47:37,645
<i>secure in the knowledge</i>

756
00:47:38,196 --> 00:47:40,698
that we did the right thing.

757
00:47:40,733 --> 00:47:42,734
<i>( Applause, cheering )</i>

758
00:47:51,791 --> 00:47:53,792
<i>( line ringing )</i>

759
00:48:00,333 --> 00:48:02,167
Man:
<i>Polk residence.</i>

760
00:48:15,181 --> 00:48:18,149
I left my wallet
at the depot in Santa Fe.

761
00:48:18,184 --> 00:48:20,151
I swear I'll set
the land-speed record.

762
00:48:20,186 --> 00:48:22,487
( Chuckles )

763
00:48:22,522 --> 00:48:26,358
Listen, I lost my
mother this week, okay?

764
00:48:28,361 --> 00:48:29,995
- All right, then.
- Thank you.

765
00:48:30,029 --> 00:48:31,196
Go ahead.

766
00:49:07,400 --> 00:49:09,784
<i>( Thunder rumbles )</i>

767
00:49:43,436 --> 00:49:45,570
I know I broke
protocol, but--

768
00:49:45,605 --> 00:49:47,105
Get in.

769
00:49:56,115 --> 00:49:58,867
I, uh...

770
00:49:58,918 --> 00:50:01,586
The car.
I have a flat tire, so--

771
00:50:01,621 --> 00:50:04,255
You. The thespian.

772
00:50:04,290 --> 00:50:06,458
The role of a lifetime.

773
00:50:06,460 --> 00:50:08,009
Germans or Soviets?

774
00:50:09,295 --> 00:50:12,764
Uh, there's
some kind of mix-up.

775
00:50:12,798 --> 00:50:16,468
You are in a world of trouble
from sea to shining sea.

776
00:50:16,470 --> 00:50:18,269
I am your only friend,

777
00:50:18,304 --> 00:50:21,439
so I advise you to
think very carefully

778
00:50:21,474 --> 00:50:23,775
about your next answer.

779
00:50:23,809 --> 00:50:25,944
Who recruited him?

780
00:50:29,315 --> 00:50:30,982
What?

781
00:50:30,984 --> 00:50:33,318
Frank Winter recruited you.

782
00:50:33,369 --> 00:50:34,986
<i>Who recruited Frank Winter?</i>

783
00:50:37,490 --> 00:50:39,491
( gasping )

784
00:50:50,553 --> 00:50:53,138
<i>( thunder crashes )</i>

785
00:50:58,844 --> 00:51:00,895
-<i> ( music playing on radio )</i>
- ( choking )

786
00:51:10,356 --> 00:51:11,690
<i>( gunshot )</i>

787
00:51:11,741 --> 00:51:13,742
- ( shrieks )
-<i> ( music continues )</i>

788
00:51:16,362 --> 00:51:18,663
( breathing quickly )

789
00:51:21,834 --> 00:51:24,369
( panting )

790
00:51:30,760 --> 00:51:32,844
You all right?

791
00:51:36,382 --> 00:51:38,049
Get the legs.

792
00:51:43,389 --> 00:51:45,890
<i>( Thunder crashes )</i>

793
00:51:53,399 --> 00:51:55,200
Pellegrin: <i>You want a
volunteer to climb</i>

794
00:51:55,234 --> 00:51:57,318
-<i> a 100-foot steel lightning rod.</i>
- Charlie: Yes.

795
00:51:57,369 --> 00:51:59,204
Fritz: To babysit Shiva,
the God of Death,

796
00:51:59,238 --> 00:52:00,739
in the middle of
an electrical storm.

797
00:52:00,790 --> 00:52:03,908
Well, maybe the Japs
can spare a kamikaze pilot.

798
00:52:03,959 --> 00:52:06,544
- I'll do it.
- No way.

799
00:52:06,579 --> 00:52:09,581
If the colonel wants to double-check
the detonators, he can do it himself.

800
00:52:09,583 --> 00:52:12,217
No wife. No kids.
I'll do it.

801
00:52:12,251 --> 00:52:14,552
No, you're more
valuable on the ground.

802
00:52:14,587 --> 00:52:17,589
- Jim, you don't have to.
- It's okay.

803
00:52:18,340 --> 00:52:20,592
It should be
someone you trust.

804
00:52:31,270 --> 00:52:34,272
Man:
<i>Hey! Hey, you!</i>

805
00:52:36,275 --> 00:52:38,515
The Boy Wonder
said to give you this.

806
00:52:57,930 --> 00:53:00,799
Start the clock.

807
00:53:00,850 --> 00:53:03,468
Zero minus 160 minutes.

808
00:53:03,519 --> 00:53:06,805
By 0430 hours,

809
00:53:06,856 --> 00:53:08,606
every tent,
including this one,

810
00:53:08,641 --> 00:53:11,442
will be collapsed
and loaded for transport

811
00:53:11,477 --> 00:53:13,629
to the 10,000-meter
perimeter.

812
00:53:15,632 --> 00:53:19,268
And if anyone sees Dr. Frank
Winter on the premises,

813
00:53:19,302 --> 00:53:20,469
arrest him.

814
00:53:21,855 --> 00:53:24,306
If he resists,
you have the authority

815
00:53:24,357 --> 00:53:27,109
to use all necessary force.

816
00:53:28,945 --> 00:53:30,980
<i>( Thunder crashing )</i>

817
00:53:56,673 --> 00:53:59,008
<i>( thunder crashes )</i>

